1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,370
A committee or group is in session.

2
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:07,730
The purpose, to consider names for a promotion, a new job, a club membership,

3
00:00:07,760 --> 00:00:13,570
an honor, someone to be the new company president, the new supervisor, the new sales manager.

4
00:00:13,839 --> 00:00:16,050
A name is placed before the group.

5
00:00:16,159 --> 00:00:19,970
The chairman asks, what is your feeling about so-and-so?

6
00:00:20,399 --> 00:00:22,050
Comments come forth.

7
00:00:22,319 --> 00:00:26,929
For some names, there are positive remarks, such as, He's a good fellow.

8
00:00:27,039 --> 00:00:29,010
People there speak highly of him.

9
00:00:29,119 --> 00:00:31,570
He has a good technical background, too.

10
00:00:32,319 --> 00:00:36,770
Mr. F. Oh, he's a personable sort of man, very human.

11
00:00:36,879 --> 00:00:39,489
I believe he would fit in well with our group.

12
00:00:40,080 --> 00:00:43,489
Some names draw negative, lukewarm statements.

13
00:00:43,759 --> 00:00:46,770
I think we should investigate that fellow carefully.

14
00:00:46,879 --> 00:00:49,649
He doesn't seem to get along too well with people.

15
00:00:49,920 --> 00:00:55,249
I know he has a good academic and technical background, I don't question his competence,

16
00:00:55,360 --> 00:00:58,850
but I am concerned about the acceptance he would receive.

17
00:00:59,039 --> 00:01:02,050
He doesn't command much respect from people.

18
00:01:02,559 --> 00:01:06,050
Now, here is an exceptionally important observation.

19
00:01:06,239 --> 00:01:12,450
In at least nine cases out of ten, the likability factor is the first thing mentioned.

20
00:01:12,640 --> 00:01:21,170
And in an overwhelmingly large number of cases, the likability factor is given far more weight than the technical factor.

21
00:01:21,839 --> 00:01:26,850
This holds true even in selecting scholars for university professorships.

22
00:01:26,959 --> 00:01:36,450
In my own academic experience, I've sat in on a considerable number of occasions when names for new faculty personnel were under question.

23
00:01:36,719 --> 00:01:42,610
When a name came up, the group would weigh most carefully thoughts such as, will he fit in?

24
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:44,209
Will students like him?

25
00:01:44,319 --> 00:01:47,089
Will he cooperate with others on the staff?

26
00:01:47,599 --> 00:01:48,450
Unfair?

27
00:01:48,559 --> 00:01:49,730
Unacademic?

28
00:01:49,839 --> 00:01:50,290
No.

29
00:01:50,479 --> 00:01:57,170
If the fellow isn't likable, he can't be expected to get through to his students with maximum effectiveness.

30
00:01:57,839 --> 00:01:59,489
Mark this point well.

31
00:01:59,759 --> 00:02:05,570
A person is not pulled up to a higher level job, rather he is lifted up.

32
00:02:05,759 --> 00:02:11,809
In this day and age, nobody has time or patience to pull another up the job ladder,

33
00:02:11,809 --> 00:02:13,809
degree by painful degree.

34
00:02:14,080 --> 00:02:19,089
The individual is chosen whose record makes him stand higher than the rest.

35
00:02:20,399 --> 00:02:26,529
We are lifted to higher levels by those who know us as likable, personable individuals.

36
00:02:26,799 --> 00:02:34,770
Every friend you make lifts you just one notch higher, and being likable makes you lighter to lift.

37
00:02:35,440 --> 00:02:39,969
Successful people follow a plan for liking people, do you?

38
00:02:40,640 --> 00:02:46,209
People who reach the top don't discuss much their techniques for thinking right toward people.

39
00:02:46,320 --> 00:02:54,209
But you would be surprised how many really big people have a clear, definite, even written plan for liking people.

40
00:02:54,880 --> 00:02:58,130
Consider the case of President Lyndon Johnson.

41
00:02:58,159 --> 00:03:05,729
Long before he became president, Johnson, in the process of developing his amazing power of personal persuasion,

42
00:03:05,919 --> 00:03:09,170
developed his own ten-point formula for success.

43
00:03:09,599 --> 00:03:16,209
His rules, which even a casual observer of the President can see are practiced in everything he does,

44
00:03:16,320 --> 00:03:18,050
are quoted directly.

45
00:03:18,050 --> 00:03:19,570
1.

46
00:03:19,839 --> 00:03:21,649
Learn to remember names.

47
00:03:21,760 --> 00:03:27,570
Inefficiency at this point may indicate that your interest is not sufficiently outgoing.

